t twenty years. A profile of the former chef to Kim Jong Il of North Korea describes Kim’s exacting standards for gourmet fare, which he gorges himself on while his country starves. A journalist becomes part of the inner circle of an IRA cell thanks to his drinking buddies. And a young, inexperienced female journalist shares mud crab in a foxhole with an equally young Hamid Karzai. Along with tales of deprivation and repression are stories of generosity and pleasure, sometimes overlapping. This memorable collection, introduced and edited by Matt McAllester, is seasoned by tragedy and violence, spiced with humor and good will, and fortified, in McAllester’s words, with "a little more humanity than we can usually slip into our newspapers and magazine stories."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFood habitsvAnecdotes. 0aForeign correspondentsvAnecdotes. 0aSurvival and emergency rationsvAnecdotes. 0aWar and societyvAnecdotes. 0aWar correspondentsvAnecdotes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Customs & Traditions.2bisacsh  aafghanistan war.  acombat.  afemale journalists.  afighting.  afood and culture.  afood and north korea.  afood and war.  afood culture and history.  afood during war.  afood history.  afood literature.  afood lovers.  afoodie lit.  ainternational cuisine.  ainternational journalism.  ajournalism and war.  ajournalism in conflict zones.  ajournalism stories.  akim jong ii.  alife of a journalist.  amiddle east journalism.  amodern journalism.  apalestinian militants.  awar and hunger.  awar in middle east.  awar journalists.  awar stories.  awar zone reporters.1 aAnderson, Jon Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Jason, econ